<body> 
<a href="mainpage.html"> GO TO MAIN PAGE </a> <br>

<h1> Chapter 1: Computer System </h2>
<b> Introduction </b>
<p> Computer is an electronic device device derived from the Latin word "computere" which means to calculate. It accepts raw facts and figures as an input which are isolated and uninterpreted through input device, process it according to the requirement of the user or command supplied by the user, store it before and after processing of require and produce a meaningful information as an output through an output device. Generally, computer works on IPO (Input-Process-Output) cycle. It follows GIGO (Garbage In Garbage Out) algorithm which means the output is always based on the input supplied by the user. The basic operation of computer is illustrated by following block diagram.
</p>
<h3> Characteristics of computer </h3>
<ul style="color: green">
<li> Accuracy </li>
<li> Speed </li>
<li> Diligence </li>
<li> Versatility </li>
<li> Storage </li>
</ul>
<h3> Pros of Computer </h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Computer is capable of handling larger volume of data and can store huge amount of data.</li>
        <li>Computer can perform millions of instructions within a limited time frame with the same speed and accuracy.</li>
        <li>Computers are used to fulfill the general requirement of users.</li>
        <li>It provides a faster and cheaper way for communication.</li>
        <li>Computers are used to solve complex and critical situations in which the involvement of humans is almost impossible.</li>
    </ol>
<h3> Cons of Computer </h3>
<ol>
        <li>Computer is a dull machine, it cannot make decisions on its own.</li>
        <li>Computer requires electricity or battery in order to operate.</li>
        <li>It can affect the human eye when used for a long period of time.</li>
        <li>It requires several peripheral devices and software to run.</li>
        <li>It cannot think, learn, or react like humans.</li>
        <li>It cannot draw conclusions or provide feedback.</li>
    </ol>
<h3>Generations of Computers</h3>
    <p>History of computers dates back to the mechanical era where computers were not used for general purposes. It took a long period of time to reach this phase. The development of computers passed through different eras, from mechanical to electromechanical to digital computers. The development in different electronic components, precise engineering, and hi-tech technology has drastically changed the operation of computers. Earlier, computers were only used for specific purposes such as counting and performing basic mathematical operations. Later on, due to the necessity and requirements of users, different general-purpose computers were developed. Therefore, the classification of computers based on their major electronic components, architecture, and modes of operation is known as the generations of computers. Below are the five different generations of computers along with their distinct features:</p>
    
    <h4>1. First Generation Computers (1946-1958)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Used vacuum tubes as their basic electronic components to control and amplify electronic signals.</li>
        <li>They were large in size, consumed a lot of electricity, and generated a large amount of heat, requiring air conditioning systems to keep the devices cool.</li>
        <li>Unreliable and prone to frequent hardware failures.</li>
        <li>Not used for commercial purposes.</li>
        <li>Machine-level language was used to program these computers.</li>
        <li>Examples: ENIAC, EDVAC, EDSAC, UNIVAC</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>2. Second Generation Computers (1959-1964)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Used transistors as their basic electronic components.</li>
        <li>Smaller in size compared to first-generation computers, consuming less electricity and generating less heat.</li>
        <li>More reliable and less prone to hardware failure.</li>
        <li>Still not used for commercial purposes as production was difficult and costly.</li>
        <li>Assembly language was used to program these computers.</li>
        <li>Examples: IBM 7000, IBM 1401, IBM 1620, NCR 304, MARK III, ATLAS</li>
        <li>Note: The first computer brought to Nepal was the IBM 1401 for the population census of 2028 BS.</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>3. Third Generation Computers (1965-1974)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Used Integrated Circuits (ICs) as their basic electronic components.</li>
        <li>Smaller in size, consumed less electricity, and generated less heat.</li>
        <li>Faster and more reliable compared to first and second-generation computers.</li>
        <li>Widely used for commercial applications all over the world.</li>
        <li>High-level languages were used to program these computers.</li>
        <li>Examples: PDP-8, PDP-11, ICL 2900 series, IBM 360, IBM 370</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>4. Fourth Generation Computers (1975-1990)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Used VLSI (Very Large Scale Integrated Circuits) as their main electronic components.</li>
        <li>Size was drastically reduced, making them more portable.</li>
        <li>Faster processing and much more reliable.</li>
        <li>Had larger memory, up to GB and TB.</li>
        <li>Used advanced high-level languages to program these computers.</li>
        <li>Examples: Apple Macintosh, IBM PC</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>5. Fifth Generation Computers (1990 - onwards)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Used ULSIC (Ultra Large Scale Integrated Circuits) or microprocessors as their major electronic components.</li>
        <li>Have or will have artificial intelligence capabilities.</li>
        <li>Feature extremely high processing power due to parallel processing.</li>
        <li>Capable of image processing, speech or voice recognition.</li>
        <li>Use various high-level languages to program these computers.</li>
    </ul>
<h3> Components of Computer System <h3>
<table border="2" cellpadding="10">
        <tr>
            <th>Input Unit</th>
            <th>Processing Unit</th>
            <th>Output Unit</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>
                Input devices accept data and instructions from the user. The device or unit used to feed raw facts and figures to the computer system for processing, along with a set of instructions, is called the input unit.
            </td>
            <td>
                The CPU is the brain of any computer system. Like in the human body, all major decisions are made by the brain. Similarly, in a computer, all major calculations and comparisons are made inside the CPU. The CPU is also responsible for activating and controlling the operation of other units of a computer system. A microprocessor is a single chip that performs the function of the CPU in microcomputers.
            </td>
            <td>
                The job of an output unit is the reverse of an input unit. It supplies information and the results of computation to the outside world. Thus, it links the computer with the external environment. It consists of devices that translate information processed by the computer into a form that humans can understand.
            </td>
        </tr>
    </table>
<h2>Computer Memory and Classification</h2>

    <div>
        <h2>1) Primary Memory/Main Memory</h2>
        <p>
            Primary Memory is also known as the main memory of a computer. This is the place where our data and instructions are stored before processing, and the results are stored before displaying the output. Memory which stores data and information currently being used by the computer is known as primary memory.
        </p>

        <h3>Features of Primary Memory:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>It is not used to store data permanently.</li>
            <li>It is usually volatile except ROM.</li>
            <li>It is usually expensive and faster than secondary storage.</li>
            <li>It is normally used for smaller storage.</li>
            <li>It is not used to transfer data from one computer to another computer.</li>
            <li>It is made up of semiconducting material.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>There are two types of Primary Memory:</h3>
        <table>
<tr>
<td>
        <h4>1.1) RAM (Random Access Memory)</h4>
        <p>RAM stores data and instructions temporarily. It is volatile, meaning data is erased when the power is cut off. RAM is a read-write memory.</p>

        <h5>Types of RAM:</h5>
        <ul>
            <li><b>SRAM (Static Random Access Memory)</b>: Made up of transistors. It doesn't need periodic refreshing like DRAM. It is faster but consumes more power.</li>
            <li><b>DRAM (Dynamic Random Access Memory)</b>: Made up of capacitors. It needs to be refreshed periodically. It is slower and consumes less power than SRAM.</li>
        </ul>
</td>
<td>
        <h4>1.2) ROM (Read Only Memory)</h4>
        <p>ROM stores data permanently and is non-volatile. Data remains intact even when the power is off. It is used for storing firmware and the boot-up program.</p>

        <h5>Types of ROM:</h5>
        <ul>
            <li><b>PROM (Programmable ROM)</b>: Can be programmed once by using a special machine.</li>
            <li><b>EPROM (Erasable Programmable ROM)</b>: Can be reprogrammed by erasing data using ultraviolet light.</li>
            <li><b>EEPROM (Electrically Erasable Programmable ROM)</b>: Can be erased and reprogrammed multiple times using electrical pulses.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <div>
        <h2>2) Secondary Memory/Auxiliary Memory</h2>
        <p>Secondary memory stores data permanently for future reference. It is non-volatile and remains intact without power. It has a huge storage capacity, and it is also known as auxiliary memory.</p>

        <h3>Types of Secondary Memory:</h3>
        <table>
    <tr>
        <td>
            <h4>2.1) Magnetic Storage</h4>
            <p>Data is stored in the form of magnetic spots. Magnetic materials are used to store data on devices like hard disks and floppy disks.</p>
            <h5>Examples of Magnetic Storage:</h5>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Hard Disk</b>: A sealed disk consisting of multiple magnetic platters. It is used for storing large volumes of data.</li>
                <li><b>Floppy Disk</b>: A round, flat disk used for storing data, much smaller in capacity compared to hard disks.</li>
            </ul>
        </td>
        <td>
            <h4>2.2) Optical Storage</h4>
            <p>Optical storage uses laser beams to read and write data. It is used for storing large amounts of data on optical disks such as CDs and DVDs.</p>
            <h5>Examples of Optical Storage:</h5>
            <ul>
                <li><b>CD-ROM</b>: Can store up to 700 MB of data. It is used for storing software, videos, and audio.</li>
                <li><b>DVD</b>: Can store more data than CD-ROM and is used for storing even larger files.</li>
            </ul>
        </td>
        <td>
            <h4>2.3) Flash Memory</h4>
            <p>Flash memory is a non-volatile, erasable, and programmable solid-state memory made of semiconductor chips. It is commonly used in devices like memory cards, USB drives, etc.</p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
    <div>

        <h2>Classification of Computers on the Basis of Size</h2>

        <p>As technology has evolved, the size of computers has drastically reduced. The development of various electronic components has enabled this reduction. Computers are classified based on their size as follows:</p>
        <table>
<tr>
<td>
        <h4>Super Computer</h4>
        Supercomputers are the fastest and most powerful computers. They are used for specialized tasks such as weather forecasting and rocket launching. Due to their size and cost, they are not commercially successful.
</td>
<td>
        <h4>Mainframe Computer</h4>
        Mainframe computers are large, fast, and expensive. They have high processing power and are used for large-scale tasks like population census and industrial applications.
</td>
<td>
        <h4>Mini Computer</h4>
        Mini computers are smaller than mainframes and are more affordable. They are often used by businesses and industries for medium-sized tasks.
</td>
<td>
        <h4>Micro Computer</h4>
        Microcomputers are small, low-cost computers that use microprocessors as their main processing unit. Examples include desktops, laptops, and palmtops.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
        <a href="chap2.html"> Next Chapter </a>
</body>
</html>




