<h1> Chapter 2:  Number System, Conversion and Boolean Logic </h1>
<h2>Boolean Operator and Operands</h2>

    <p>
        Operators are the symbols that define the specific operation. These are three basic operators used in Boolean Algebra, i.e. AND, OR, NOT. Every other operation can be expressed in terms of these basic operations. For example, the NOR operator is the combination of NOT and OR operators. The three basic operators are:
    </p>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h2>a. AND Operators</h2>
    AND operator is represented by “.” So, A AND B is represented by (A.B). The result of the AND operation is exactly the same as simple arithmetic multiplication. That means the result will be high (1) only when both the inputs are high. Note: A AND B can also be represented by AˆB or AnB.
   </td>
<td>
 <h3>Truth table of AND operation:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>Y = A.B</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h2>b. OR Operator</h2>
    OR operator is represented by “+” So, A OR B is represented by (A+B). The result of the OR operation is exactly the same as simple arithmetic addition. That means the result will be low (0) if and only if both the inputs are low. Note: A OR B can also be represented by AvB or AuB.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>Truth table of OR operation:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>Y = A+B</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h2>c. NOT Operator</h2>
    NOT operator is represented by “-” or “’”. So, NOT operation of an operand A is represented as A’. The NOT operation performs negation, meaning it will give high output (1) for low input (0) and vice-versa.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>Truth table of NOT operation:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>A'</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h2>Logic Gate</h2>
    <p>A logic gate is an electronic circuit that operates on one or more inputs to produce an output. Logic gates are used for binary operations, which are fundamental components for modern digital computers. Logic gates are embedded in an Integrated Circuit (IC). Each gate has its specific function and graphical symbol. In digital computers, there are three basic logic gates:</p>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>a. AND Gate</h3>
    <p>AND Gate is an electronic circuit that produces high output (1) only when both the inputs are high. The output is the same as the result of basic arithmetic multiplication. This gate may have more than two inputs and produce a single output.</p>
    <h3>Truth table for AND gate:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>Y = A.B</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>b. OR Gate</h3>
    <p>OR Gate is an electronic circuit that produces low output (0) when all the inputs are low (0) and produces high (1) output for every possible combination of 0 and 1. The output is the same as basic binary addition. The gate may have two or more than two inputs and produce a single result.</p>
    <h3>Truth table for OR gate:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>Y = A+B</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>c. NOT Gate</h3>
    <p>NOT Gate is another fundamental gate whose result is the complement of its input. It is also called an inverter. It produces low (0) logic for high (1) input and vice-versa. This Gate has a single input and a single output.</p>
    <h3>Truth table for NOT gate:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>A'</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>d. NAND Gate</h3>
    <p>NAND gate is a derived gate from NOT and AND gates. This gate inverts the output obtained from the AND gate. That means it will produce low (0) output when both the inputs are high (1) and produce high (1) output when any one of the inputs is low (0).</p>
    <h3>Truth table for NAND gate:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>A.B</th>
            <th>Y = (A.B)′</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>e. NOR Gate</h3>
    <p>NOR gate is derived from the combination of OR gate and NOT gate. This gate inverts the output obtained from the OR gate.</p>
    <h3>Truth table for NOR gate:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>A+B</th>
            <th>Y = (A+B)′</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>f. Exclusive OR (X-OR)</h3>
    <p>X-OR gate generates a low (0) output when both the inputs are either low (0) or high (1). It gives high (1) output only when one of the inputs is high (1).</p>
    <h3>Truth table for X-OR gate:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>A'</th>
            <th>B'</th>
            <th>A'.B</th>
            <th>A.B'</th>
            <th>A'.B + A.B'</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>g. Exclusive NOR (X-NOR)</h3>
    <p>X-NOR gate generates a high (1) output when both the inputs are either low (0) or high (1). It gives low (0) output only when one of the inputs is high (1).</p>
    <h3>Truth table for X-NOR gate:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>A'</th>
            <th>B'</th>
            <th>A.B</th>
            <th>A'.B'</th>
            <th>A.B + A'.B'</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h2>De-Morgan's Theorem</h2>
<table style="color:blue; background-color:yellow">
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>First Theorem</h3>
    <p>The first theorem states that: “The complement of a sum equals the product of its complement.”</p>
    <p>It is represented as: (A + B)’ = A’.B’</p>

    <h3>Proof of First Theorem:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>(A+B)</th>
            <th>(A+B)’</th>
            <th>A'</th>
            <th>B'</th>
            <th>A'.B'</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>Second Theorem</h3>
    <p>The second theorem states that: “The complement of a product equals the sum of its complement.”</p>
    <p>It is represented as: (A.B)’ = A’ + B’</p>

    <h3>Proof of Second Theorem:</h3>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>A</th>
            <th>B</th>
            <th>(A.B)</th>
            <th>(A.B)’</th>
            <th>A'</th>
            <th>B'</th>
            <th>A' + B'</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>0</td>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>0</td>
