<h1>Chapter 3: Software </h1>
    
    <p>As we know, stand-alone hardware cannot do anything. For the smooth operation of our Computer System, there should be proper coordination between hardware and software. Software helps to mobilize the hardware and other resources. In order to mobilize hardware, we have to write several sets of instructions which instruct the computer what to do and what not to do. These sets of instructions are collectively known as a program, and the term software is the collection of related programs and associated documents.</p>

    <p>In order to produce useful output, hardware and software must work together. Nothing useful can be done with hardware only, and software cannot be utilized without hardware.</p>

    <h2>The different types of software are:</h2>
    <h3>1) System Software</h3>
    <p>System software is a set of one or more programs designed to control the operation of our computer system. This type of software doesn't fulfill the specific requirements of the user. They are general programs written to assist humans in the use of the computer system. System software supports the running of other software, communicates with peripheral devices, supports the development of other types of software, and monitors the use of various hardware resources. Thus, the system software makes the operation of the computer system more effective and efficient.</p>

    <h4>1.1) System Management</h4>
    <p>System management is responsible for proper management and functioning of the computer system. All types of management between computer hardware and software are performed by system management software. There are 3 types of system management software:</p>
    <table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h5>1.1.1) Operating System</h5>
    <p>The operating system is a collection of programs that control the overall operation of the computer system. It is the first program that is loaded into memory when the computer is turned on. It provides a platform for other application programs to run and execute. It provides users with an interface so that they can easily communicate with the computer. For example, Linux, Windows, Mac, etc.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h5>1.1.2) Utility Software</h5>
    <p>Utility software is supporting software that performs specific tasks related to the maintenance of the computer system. Some utility software is included in the operating system, while others are available separately in the market. They are also called service programs. Examples include Norton Utility, PC Tools, WinZip, etc.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h5>1.1.3) Device Driver</h5>
    <p>A device driver is a software responsible for the smooth functioning of hardware devices connected to the computer. When a new device is added, a new software called a device driver is installed. The driver coordinates with the operating system to ensure that the newly installed hardware functions properly.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h4>1.2) System Development</h4>
    <p>System development refers to a set of programs used to develop computer programs. This type of software is not used by a normal user but by programmers for the development of new programs. There are two types of system development software:</p>
    <table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h5>1.2.1) Programming Language</h5>
    <p>The language with which instructions are given to the computer is known as the programming language. Programming languages consist of keywords, variables, operators, loops, and other symbols. They help facilitate communication between the computer and the user. There are two types of programming languages: low-level language and high-level language.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h5>1.2.2) Language Translator</h5>
    <p>A language translator is a special software that translates programs written in one language into another language. This translation is necessary for both low-level and high-level languages. The types of language translators include compilers, interpreters, and assemblers.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h3>2) Application Software</h3>
    <p>Application software is a set of one or more programs designed to perform a specific task. These programs are developed to fulfill user demands and direct the computer to solve user-oriented problems, such as preparing bills, calculating equations, and creating mark sheets. Examples include MS-Excel, Photoshop, billing software, etc.</p>
<table>
<Tr>
<td>
    <h4>2.1) Packaged Software</h4>
    <p>Packaged software is a generalized set of programs designed and developed for general purposes. These software are generally large-sized, error-free, advanced, and standard, offering much functionality for special work. While these software might not perfectly match the requirements of many organizations, they are developed by reputed software companies and are considered trustworthy. Examples include MS-Office, Adobe, Macromedia, etc.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h4>2.2) Customized / Tailored Software</h4>
    <p>Customized software is developed for specific tasks, aimed at solving specific problems for specific users or organizations. The requirements of the user or organization are perfectly matched, and these software can be easily changed since they are developed by local programmers. Examples include payroll systems, inventory management, school management, billing software, and mark sheet evaluation systems.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <hr>

    <h1>Operating System - Introduction</h1>
    
    <p>An operating system (OS) is an integrated set of programs that controls overall resources such as the CPU, memory, and input-output devices of a computer system. The major objective of an operating system is to improve the performance and efficiency of a computer system. Like the manager of a company, an operating system is responsible for the smooth and efficient functioning of the entire computer system.</p>

    <p>The operating system provides a platform for other application programs/software to run and execute. It provides users with an interface so that they can easily communicate with the computer, making it more convenient to use and operate.</p>

    <p>An operating system is a collection of programs that controls the overall operation of the computer system. It also controls and coordinates the use of hardware among various application programs for different users. It acts as an interface between the user and the computer hardware. The other major functions of an operating system are:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>It controls, monitors, and coordinates the overall operation of the computer system.</li>
        <li>It acts as an interface between the user and the computer.</li>
        <li>It provides a platform to develop, run, and execute other computer programs.</li>
        <li>It manages hardware resources such as the CPU, memory, input-output terminals, networking equipment, etc.</li>
        <li>It hides programming and hardware complexity from the user.</li>
    </ul>
<h1>Types of Operating System (OS)</h1>
    
    <h2>A) On the basis of processing</h2>

    <h3>1) Multi-programming OS</h3>
    <p>Multi-programming is used in a multi-user environment. It is a technique in which multiple user programs are executed simultaneously by a single processor. Multi-programming means when two or more programs are provided to the CPU for processing or loaded in the internal storage of the CPU at the same time. Once the portion of one program is executed, the portion of another program is executed, and so on. Thus, multi-programming refers to the concurrent execution of several programs. The main purpose of multi-programming is to increase the utilization of computer and its resources. Different forms of multi-programming OS are multi-tasking, multi-processing, and multi-user.</p>

    <h3>2) Multi-tasking OS</h3>
    <p>Multi-tasking OS allows more than one program to run concurrently, mainly in a single user system. These computers are capable of executing several tasks or programs at the same time. For executing several tasks, it can be a single or multi-processing system. In some multi-tasking systems, one of the processes is called foreground (active), while others are called background (inactive). Multi-tasking OS increases the productivity of the user by executing many tasks simultaneously. Examples include MS-Windows, Linux, MAC OS, etc.</p>

    <h3>3) Multiprocessing OS</h3>
    <p>Multi-processing systems have more than one processor linked in a coordinated way. Multiprocessing OS supports running a program on more than one CPU. Generally, super servers are especially designed to support multiple processors. UNIX is commonly used as a multi-processing OS. Multi-programming and multi-processing are not the same concept. Multi-programming involves the concurrent execution of two or more programs by a single CPU, whereas multi-processing involves two or more processors (CPUs) controlling the different activities or executing many programs simultaneously. This concept is also known as parallel processing. It is a more costly and complex technique than multi-programming, dramatically increasing the program execution speed of the computer.</p>

    <h3>4) Time-Sharing OS</h3>
    <p>Time-sharing is a technique that enables many people located in various terminals to use a particular computer system at the same time. Processor time, shared among multiple users simultaneously, is termed as time-sharing. Multiple jobs are executed by the CPU by switching between them, but the switches occur so frequently that users can receive an immediate response.</p>
    <h4>Advantages:</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Provides quick response.</li>
        <li>Reduces CPU idle time.</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Disadvantages:</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Problem of reliability.</li>
        <li>Less security.</li>
        <li>Integrity issues.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>5) Batch Processing OS</h3>
    <p>Batch processing is a technique in which similar jobs are grouped together, consisting of programs, data, and system commands. This type of processing is suitable for programs that involve large completion or calculations, like payroll, weather forecasting, or statistical analysis. Users need not wait while the job is being processed. They can submit their program to the operator and collect it later. Jobs are stored on a disk in a batch or queue and executed one after another under the control of the OS.</p>
    <p>The major disadvantage of batch processing is that it does not allow interaction between the user and the program during execution.</p>

    <h3>6) Multi-threading OS</h3>
    <p>A program in execution is known as a process and can be divided into multiple smaller sub-processes. These sub-processes are known as threads. Multi-threading OS has the ability to divide processes into threads and execute them concurrently. Threads are individual processes that execute simultaneously in multi-tasking OS.</p>

    <h3>7) Real-time OS</h3>
    <p>Real-time processing is one that controls the environment by receiving data and taking action quickly to affect the functioning of the environment at the same instant. It is an online processing system where processing time is critical. The entire processing task has to be completed in a predefined time. Real-time OS is suitable for operations such as:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Airlines or flight seat availability</li>
        <li>Rocket launching systems</li>
        <li>Wholesale supplier and manufacturer systems</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>8) Online Processing OS</h3>
    <p>Online processing is a popular processing technique in which transactions are processed as soon as they happen at the place of origin. It is simpler compared to real-time OS. In this method, users can interact or provide input during processing. The output is provided back to the user as soon as the processing is completed.</p>

    <h2>B) On the basis of User Interface (UI)</h2>
    <p>A user interface allows users to interact with the computer system. It provides an ideal environment to enhance user experience and interaction with the computer. There are two main types of user interfaces:</p>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>1) Character User Interface (CUI)</h3>
    <p>CUI is a type of operating system in which the computer operates based on commands issued by the user. All operations require specific commands, making it non-user-friendly. Only individuals with technical knowledge can operate such systems. It is a primitive type of OS where graphics, pictures, icons, drop-down menus, and dialogue boxes are not used, making it harder to use. CUI uses the text mode of a computer, such as MS-DOS and UNIX. A command prompt is a sequence of characters used in CUI. Commands are typed in to instruct the computer.</p>
    
    <h4>Features of CUI:</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Single-user, single-tasking operating system.</li>
        <li>Less user-friendly compared to GUI.</li>
        <li>Commands are used to instruct the computer.</li>
        <li>Requires the user to remember commands.</li>
        <li>Cannot display graphics or multimedia.</li>
        <li>Faster than GUI systems.</li>
        <li>Does not recognize pointing devices like mouse or joystick.</li>
        <li>Can be used in low memory and low processing power computers.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>2) Graphical User Interface (GUI)</h3>
    <p>GUI is an operating system in which computers are operated by clicking or selecting icons or dialogue boxes instead of typing direct commands. Graphics such as icons, pictures, drop-down menus, and dialogue boxes make it more user-friendly than CUI. Since the user does not need to remember commands, it is easy to use for non-technical people. The main goal of a GUI is to create an environment where the user can operate the computer without training or remembering commands. Examples of GUI operating systems include Windows, MAC OS, etc.</p>

    <h4>Features of GUI:</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>User-friendly interface.</li>
        <li>No need to remember commands.</li>
        <li>Supports full multimedia and animation.</li>
        <li>Requires larger memory for processing.</li>
        <li>Can be used in network environments.</li>
        <li>Multi-tasking, multi-programming, and multi-user OS.</li>
        <li>Supports a wide variety of peripheral devices.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h4>Basic Components of GUI:</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Icon:</strong> Small pictures that represent commands, files, or windows.</li>
        <li><strong>Pointer:</strong> A symbol (usually an angled arrow) controlled by a pointing device (e.g., mouse, trackpad).</li>
        <li><strong>Desktop:</strong> The area on the display screen where icons are grouped.</li>
        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Areas on the screen that can be resized and used for running different programs or displaying information.</li>
        <li><strong>Menus:</strong> Lists from which users can select commands.</li>
        <li><strong>Folders:</strong> Graphical representation of a directory.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>C) On the mode of user:</h2>

    <h3>1) Single User</h3>
    <p>A single user OS is designed for use by a single user at any given time. It is most commonly used on home computers or office systems. There are two general types of single-user systems: single-user single-tasking and single-user multi-tasking. Examples of single-user single-tasking OS include MS-DOS and PC-DOS.</p>

    <h3>2) Multi-User</h3>
    <p>Multi-user OS allows multiple users at different terminals to access a single system with one OS. The multi-user OS shares computer resources among users, allowing each user a slice of the processor's time. This is also known as time-sharing. It gives users the impression that they are being served simultaneously, even though the OS serves them one at a time. Examples of multi-user OS include Linux and UNIX.</p>
