    <h1>Chapter 5: Programming </h1>
    <p>As we know, every computerized device does not work by itself. They need to be given some sort of command that makes the computer work. These commands help to instruct the computer and program specific actions required by the user. Since the commands are given in the form of a computer language, programming languages are used to write the set of instructions which command the computer to perform certain actions collectively, called programs. These programs are then integrated to make a complete software. Simply put, software is the collection of different interrelated programs that perform specific functions.</p>

    <p>The program written in any type of programming language is not understood by the computer; hence, we need some sort of language translator or processor such as an assembler, compiler, and interpreter. Their basic function is to convert programs written in any language into machine-level language.</p>

    <p>The program written by the programmer is known as the source program. After converting it, it becomes the object program.</p>

    <h2>Qualities of Good Programs</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>It should be easily understood.</li>
        <li>A program should be correct; it should be error-free.</li>
        <li>It should be reliable.</li>
        <li>It should have an easily understandable user interface.</li>
        <li>It should be portable and flexible.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Programming Language</h2>
    <p>In order to make communication between the user and computer, we need a computer language that helps the user to generate commands to perform as per the requirement. This language, with which we can give instructions to the computer, is known as a programming language. Programming languages are the set of different keywords, variables, operators, loops, and other entities using different character sets including numbers, special symbols, and alphanumeric values.</p>

    <p>Hence, the process of writing the programming language is known as programming, and the person who writes programs is called a programmer.</p>

    <h2>Types of Programming Language</h2>
    <h3>1. Low-Level Language</h3>
    <p>Low-level languages are machine-dependent languages. This means the program written for one type of system cannot be run on another system. Developers must have detailed knowledge about the system they are writing a program for. Programming in low-level languages is difficult and time-consuming.</p>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h4>a. Machine Level Language (1GL)</h4>
    <p>This language consists of a sequence of 0’s and 1’s to generate instructions. Since it uses binary numbers, this type of language is directly understood by the processor, resulting in higher execution speeds. However, it is machine-dependent.</p>

    <h5>Advantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Directly understood by the processor, leading to high execution speed.</li>
        <li>Language translator is not needed.</li>
        <li>Can be used to program specific-purpose computers.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Hard to develop and debug programs.</li>
        <li>Machine dependent; cannot be transferred across different systems.</li>
        <li>Commands are in binary, which is difficult to remember.</li>
        <li>Programmers must have detailed knowledge of the system.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
<td>
    <h4>b. Assembly Language (2GL)</h4>
    <p>Assembly language is also a low-level language. Instead of writing instructions in a series of 0’s and 1’s, we can use mnemonics like ADD, SUB, RST, etc. This language is closer to machine-level language but still requires a language translator like an assembler.</p>

    <h5>Advantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Easier to write, debug, and understand compared to machine-level language.</li>
        <li>Faster execution compared to high-level languages.</li>
        <li>Used to develop device drivers.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Machine dependent; programs written for one processor do not work on another.</li>
        <li>More complex to use due to mnemonics.</li>
        <li>Development and debugging are more difficult compared to high-level languages.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
<td>
    <h4>2. High-Level Language</h4>
    <p>High-level languages are closer to the English language, which makes it easier to develop and debug programs. These languages are machine-independent, meaning programs written for one system can work on others.</p>

    <h5>Advantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Programs are easier to write, debug, and understand.</li>
        <li>Machine-independent; programs can run on different systems.</li>
        <li>No need to remember complex mnemonics.</li>
        <li>Faster program development.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Requires translation into machine-level language before execution.</li>
        <li>Slower execution compared to low-level languages.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<hr >
<table>
<tr>
<td colspan=3 align="center">
    <h4>Classification of High-Level Languages:</h4>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<Td>
    <h5>a. Procedural-Oriented Language (3GL)</h5>
    <p>This type of language focuses on procedures or routines. It is used to express logic and procedure. It follows a top-down approach, where the main function is written at the bottom of the program.</p>

    <h5>Advantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Easier to write and debug programs compared to low-level languages.</li>
        <li>Used for general-purpose programming.</li>
        <li>Machine-independent.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Requires a language translator to execute the program.</li>
        <li>Program execution is slower compared to low-level languages.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
<td>
    <h5>b. Problem/Objective-Oriented Language (4GL)</h5>
    <p>This is an advanced form of high-level language that focuses more on data than on procedure. It uses a bottom-up approach.</p>

    <h5>Advantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Supports advanced, user-friendly software development.</li>
        <li>Machine-independent.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Requires a language translator.</li>
        <li>Execution is slower.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
<td>
    <h5>c. Natural Language (5GL)</h5>
    <p>Natural language uses common language to express commands. It's still in the development stage, with languages like PROLOG being used.</p>

    <h5>Advantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Easy to write and debug programs.</li>
        <li>Machine-independent.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>Requires a language translator.</li>
        <li>Program execution is slower.</li>
    </ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h2>Language Translator/Processor</h2>
    <p>A language translator is a system development software that converts programs written in assembly or high-level languages (source programs) into machine-level languages (object programs). Different types of language translators include:</p>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>Assembler</h3>
    An assembler converts assembly-level programs into machine-level programs.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>Compiler</h3>
    A compiler converts high-level language programs into machine-level programs in one go, but debugging can be complex and time-consuming.
</td>
<Td>
    <h3>Interpreter</h3>
    An interpreter translates one statement at a time and is easier to debug, but program execution is slower compared to a compiler.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h2>Difference Between Compiler and Interpreter</h2>
    <table border="1">
        <tr>
            <th>S.N.</th>
            <th>Compiler</th>
            <th>Interpreter</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>Translates the whole program at once.</td>
            <td>Translates one line at a time.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2</td>
            <td>Finds errors after compiling the entire program.</td>
            <td>Finds errors after translating each line.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>3</td>
            <td>Faster translation process.</td>
            <td>Slower translation process.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>4</td>
            <td>Difficult to debug.</td>
            <td>Easier to debug.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>5</td>
            <td>Requires more memory space.</td>
            <td>Requires less memory space.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>6</td>
            <td>Older programming languages.</td>
            <td>Newer programming languages.</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Syntax and Semantics</h2>
    <p>In programming, syntax refers to the structure or rules of the programming language, while semantics refers to the meaning attached to individual symbols or words.</p>

    <h2>Error (BUG)</h2>
    <p>Errors in a program are known as bugs. Bugs may arise due to poor problem analysis, incorrect language usage, or hardware failure.</p>

    <h3>Types of Errors:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Syntax Error</b>: Errors due to incorrect rules of the programming language.</li>
        <li><b>Logical Error</b>: Errors due to faulty logic.</li>
        <li><b>Runtime Error</b>: Errors that occur during the execution of the program.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Common Terminology in Programming</h2>
    <h3>Data Types</h3>
    <p>Data types specify the kind of data used in a program, such as numeric or character values.</p>

    <h3>Variables and Constants</h3>
    <p><b>Variable</b>: Holds values that can change during the program's execution.</p>
    <p><b>Constant</b>: Holds values that do not change during the program's execution.</p>

    <h3>Operands and Operators</h3>
    <p>Operands are the values on which an operation is performed. Operators are special symbols used to perform specific operations.</p>

    <h3>Types of Operators</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Arithmetic Operators: +, -, /, *</li>
        <li>Relational Operators: <, >, >=, <=, =</li>
        <li>Logical Operators: AND, OR, NOT</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Program Design Tools</h2>
    <p>Common tools for designing programs include algorithms, flowcharts, and pseudocode.</p>

    <h3>Algorithm</h3>
    <p>An algorithm is a step-by-step procedure for solving a specific problem, written in a simple, human-readable language.</p>
<h3>Flowchart</h3>
    <p>A flowchart is a diagrammatic representation of an algorithm, using standardized symbols to represent actions and decisions.</p>

    <h3>Pseudocode</h3>
    <p>Pseudocode is a high-level description of the program logic, written in simple English.</p>
<a href="chap6.html"> NEXT CHAPTER </a>
</body>
</html>


