<body>
<h1> Chapter 6: Introduction to the Internet</h1>

    <p>The Internet is the global network of networks. It is a huge collection of computers all over the world that are inter-connected to one another in various ways to form a web-net.</p>

    <h2>Components required for Internet Connections:</h2>
    <p>The basic requirements for the Internet are:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>A TCP/IP enabled computer with a web browser.</li>
        <li>An account with an ISP (Internet Service Provider).</li>
        <li>A telephone line.</li>
        <li>A MODEM to connect to the telephone line and computer.</li>
        <li>A computer with the following capacity:
            <ul>
                <li>Minimum 386 microprocessor chip with 16 MB RAM.</li>
                <li>Color monitor with 256 color support and 640x480 resolution.</li>
                <li>A hard disk of 200 MB free space.</li>
                <li>Multimedia sound card and speaker.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Internet Services and Applications</h2>
<table style="background-color: navy">
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>a) World Wide Web (WWW)</h3>
    WWW is a series of services interconnected through hypertext. It was created in 1990 by the European Particle Physics Laboratory in Geneva, Switzerland, to exchange and share data through the Internet using the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
</td>
<Td>
    <h3>b) Web Browser</h3>
    A web browser is a computer program that accesses web pages and displays them on the screen. Popular web browsers include Internet Explorer, Safari, Mozilla Firefox, Opera, etc.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>c) FTP - File Transfer Protocol</h3>
    FTP is an Internet tool that allows users to transfer files from one computer to another.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>d) Electronic Mail (E-mail)</h3>
    E-mail allows sending and receiving messages electronically over the Internet.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>e) Voicemail</h3>
    Voicemail is a service that answers telephone calls and records audio messages.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>f) USENET – View and News</h3>
    USENET is a Bulletin Board System (BBS) with thousands of newsgroups organized by topics.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>g) Chat</h3>
    Chat allows real-time communication by typing in a virtual room.
</td>
<td>

    <h3>h) IRC - Internet Relay Chat</h3>
    IRC is a multi-user live chat system that connects various servers and allows creating channels for group chats.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>i) Video Conferencing</h3>
    Video conferencing allows face-to-face communication through webcams, including sound and video.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>j) Universal Resource Locator (URL)</h3>
    URL is a unique address used to locate resources on the Internet, e.g., <code>http://www.animalplanet.com</code>.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>k) E-Fax (Electronic Fax)</h3>
    E-Fax allows sending and receiving faxes electronically over the Internet.
</td>
<td>
    <h3>l) TELNET – Remote Login</h3>
    Telnet allows users to login to a host computer from a remote system.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h2>Internet Terminologies</h2>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
    <h3>ISP (Internet Service Provider)</h3>
    <p>ISP is an organization that provides access to the Internet for a fee.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>Search Engine</h3>
    <p>Search engines are tools like Yahoo, Google, or AltaVista that help users search websites on the Internet.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>Domain Name and IP Address</h3>
    <p>Domain name is a unique address for a website. An IP address is a numeric address associated with a domain name.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>DNS Server</h3>
    <p>The DNS Server is responsible for resolving domain names into IP addresses.</p>
</td>
<td>
    <h3>Web Server</h3>
    <p>A web server stores and serves web pages to clients (browsers).</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
    <h2>Tags in HTML</h2>
    <p>HTML tags are the instructions or commands given to a web browser to organize the contents of a webpage.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Pair tags:</strong> Tags that have both opening and closing parts, e.g., <code>&lt;html&gt;...&lt;/html&gt;</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Singular tags:</strong> Tags that only have an opening part, e.g., <code>&lt;br&gt;</code>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Steps to Write and Execute an HTML Document</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Write all HTML tags, attributes, and content in a text editor (Notepad).</li>
        <li>Save your file with the .HTML extension, e.g., <code>sample.html</code>.</li>
        <li>Open the file using any web browser.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Difference between E-mail and E-Fax</h2>
    <table border="1">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>E-mail</th>
                <th>E-Fax</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>Very cheap</td>
                <td>More expensive than E-mail</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Message goes to the local server</td>
                <td>Message goes to the Internet server before reaching the destination</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Stored in the destination computer</td>
                <td>Printed directly on the destination's printer</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    
